# ADR-0005 — Expose Automations Through FastAPI

> Status: Accepted
>
> Date: 2026-07-13

---

# Context

The framework originally exposed browser automations only through its Python API.

As the project evolved, external systems needed to execute automations without embedding Python code or interacting directly with Playwright.

Typical consumers include:

- Google Apps Script
- Internal web applications
- Scheduled jobs
- External services

A stable HTTP interface became necessary.

---

# Decision

Expose browser automations through a FastAPI application.

The HTTP API becomes the public entry point of the framework.

Clients interact exclusively through HTTP endpoints.

Browser automation remains completely hidden behind the API.

---

# Architecture

```
HTTP Client

↓

FastAPI

↓

Router

↓

Service

↓

Portal

↓

Workflow

↓

Playwright
```

The API layer is intentionally thin.

Routers contain:

- request validation
- dependency injection
- response generation

Business logic remains inside the framework.

---

# Consequences

Positive:

- Browser automation becomes language-independent.
- Multiple clients can reuse the same implementation.
- OpenAPI documentation is generated automatically.
- Swagger UI is available without additional work.
- Authentication and concurrency can be centralized.

Negative:

- HTTP becomes the primary integration surface.
- Browser automation must now consider API semantics and HTTP status codes.

---

# Alternatives Considered

## Continue exposing only a Python API

Rejected.

External systems such as Google Apps Script cannot easily consume Python code.

---

## Implement a custom HTTP server

Rejected.

FastAPI already provides:

- dependency injection
- request validation
- OpenAPI
- Swagger
- mature ecosystem

---

## Build a CLI instead of an HTTP API

Rejected.

A CLI would still require process management and would not integrate naturally with external services.

---

# Rationale

FastAPI provides a stable, well-documented and production-ready interface while keeping browser automation completely isolated from transport concerns.

The chosen architecture preserves the existing framework design and enables future integrations without exposing Playwright directly.

